description:
Practice Plans is a simple application for iPhone and iPad that allows coaches/team leaders to create, edit, and share practice plans for their teams, as well as browse plans created by other users. Social/sharing features were implemented in the beta version but never released because the client chose to abandon the project.

This was written along with Hoop Coach Basketball Playbook as a freelance project for the basketball coach at my high school, as well as for the sake of getting more experience with iOS development. The app is being sold by HoopCoach.org on the app store here: 
https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/practice-plans/id455007011?mt=8

description:
App Store link: https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/benzinga-for-ios/id688949481

Benzinga Stock & News Tracker allows you to manage multiple stock watchlists and see price updates in real time. You can view zoomable graphs, news, and tweets related to a particular stock. You can also view articles from multiple channels on Benzinga.com, as well as view tweets relating to currently trending stocks.

Key skills used in this project:
-concurrent programming
-interfacing with web services through RESTKit, AFNetworking, and the Social Framework
-offline browsing & multiple methods of caching
-data persistence with Core Data, SQLite, and NSKeyedArchiver
-interactive graph drawing with Core Plot
-Unit testing with Kiwi
-Flat design principles

description:
Monarch is an iPad app that connects your profiles on Twitter, Facebook, Foursquare, LinkedIn, and many more social networking and blogging sites, making it as easy and as fast as possible to post status updates, check-ins, and images from one central location. It has earned over 10,000 downloads since its release.

Available on the App Store here:
https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/monarch-express/id391026539?mt=8

Unfortunately, since this project was abandoned two years ago, very few (if any) of the APIs still support the requests this app makes, simply because they've changed so quickly.

collaborators.contribution: I was responsible for writing the code and creating the designs for this application. The main challenge was interfacing with a large number of very different APIs with very unique protocols. These APIs included: Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, Tumblr, Blogger, Picasa, Foursquare, and Imgur. Specifically, those which used OAuth V1 for authentication proved very challenging. I'm not much of a designer, but I'm most proud of the graphic design in this app out of anything I've done.

description:
Verbosify is a funny app which, when given a string of English text, will replace each word with a longer synonym, making it as verbose as possible. The user can tap the dinosaur head to have the text read aloud in an accent of their choosing. After "Verbosifying", the user can start over, continue running the algorithm to make the text more nonsensical, or post it to their facebook wall.
Input can come from the user, from a random friend's facebook status, or from lyrics to a song of the user's choice. It utilizes two different online thesaurus APIs, words.bighugelabs.com and thesaurus.com, as well as the Flite text-to-speech library, Facebook SDK, LyricsWiki API, and the Stanford Natural Language Processing library.

collaborators.contribution: I was the sole developer of Verbosify. Key technologies I worked with include interfacing with multiple different types of APIs using both HTTP requests and built-in SDKs, determining parts of speech using the Stanford NLP library, implementing text-to-speech using Flite, XML/JSON parsing, and using the facebook SDK for authentication, wall posts, and pulling feed data.
